<h2>Cracking Open Doom .wad Files - Part 2: Audio</h2>

[UNDER CONSTRUCTION CHECK BACK LATER]

<p>
There are three formats of audio data stuffed into the WAD:
</p>

<ul>
<li>PC Speaker sound effects - <a href="https://youtu.be/jRqticdr6UE">bleep! bzz! doo-doo-doo!</a></li>
<li>Music</li>
<li>Waveform sound effects</li>
</ul>

<p>
When Doom and Wolfenstein 3-D came out most IBM Compatible (PC) computers did
not have a sound hardware or external speakers. They usually just shipped with an
internal speaker that was capable of very crude buzzing sound effects - the
"PC speaker". Games in the 80s and early 90s for PC usually played <a href="https://youtu.be/JQ3Qg3ora2I">crappy yet
charming</a> music, or crappy yet charming sound effects, but not both. Some even
had a button to switch between playback modes. Weird right? Developers got really
creative with making the PC speaker play something symbolic of car noises or
gunshots. From 1990 you could buy the original Soundblaster for proper digital
audio, but most people didn't have them - we bought one <i>because</i> of Doom.
So these games had to support both sound devices.
</p>

<p>
I ignored the PC speaker data - it didn't really grab my interest.
I'm pretty sure I saw a tweet from Tom Hall saying he
used to hand-code these speaker sounds! I really only remember going from PC speaker
sounds (pretty much all PC-speaker games sounded kind of the same TBH) <i>to</i>
Soundblaster - woooooow!
</p>

<p>
The music I expected to be MIDI - which was the de facto standard for video game
music on PC until the end of the 90s. It turns out it's not MIDI, it's a custom
format compiled <i>from</i> MIDI, to be played through custom playback software
that was never released as open source with the rest of the game code. In the
source code notes there is a note lamenting using the proprietary audio software,
and not writing their own audio code, because it couldn't be released (and I
suspect there were some other issues).
</p>

<p>
The proper sound files are also a custom third-party format, which was never
disclosed, and these things are locked away inside the binary. I know a thing or
two about audio, so I didn't really think that this special custom
format was going to be all that special or custom, plus I'm also brave AND
foolish, AND I have a hex-editor and I'm not afraid to use it!
</p>


